that Cavafy would adopt as his own, making Pater’s imaginary portraits an important touchstone for his own historicizing poetry. Cavafy would move beyond Pater to explore a more openly homoerotic sensuality but he never quite abandoned this rich Victorian legacy, one that contributed greatly to his emergence as a global poet. Jeffreys concludes by considering Cavafy’s current popularity as a gay poet and his curious relation to kitsch as manifest in his ongoing popularity via translation and visual media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDecadence in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism.  aCavafy's career, poetry, biography, aesthetic movement, cosmopolitan London, Victorian aestheticism, aestheticism in England, French literary decadence, Raphaelite painters, aesthetic writers, revolution in British literary culture,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170125240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701252423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701252/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles